Import functions

Here are a few functions I wrote up to help with implementation. Region_based_seg does all the heavy lifting.

In [2]: 
from auto_detect_beamstop import clip_at_percentile, region_based_seg

Get data

First, read in a bunch of pickles that contain numpy-converted image. I'm only doing this because cctx.python does not have a good way of adding modules, and it certainly doesn't suppoert skimage.

In [3]: 
import os
from cPickle import load

data_source = 'test_data_numpy'
files = os.listdir(data_source)
images = []
for f in files:
    im = load(open(os.path.join(data_source, f), 'rb'))
    images.append(clip_at_percentile(im, 99.9))

Now we have a list of clipped images, where we have set all pixels above the 99.9th percentile to the value at that percentile. This just deals with zingers/overloads. Very important step, do not skip

Get segmentation for images

Why these params? See other notebook... I made a histogram of all test images, and intensities below 15 are clearly the beamstop. You might be able to tweak these further, but I think they're pretty good.

In [5]: 
segmentations = []
for im in images:
    segmentations.append(region_based_seg(im, low_thresh=15, high_thresh=35))

In [22]: 
from cPickle import dump
import numpy as np
for file, seg in zip(files, segmentations):
    dump(np.array(~seg, dtype=int), open("segmentation-" + file, 'wb')) # 0=Background, 1=Beamstop

Finally, run a little cctbx script to turn these into the right bit of the image pickle. You want to get them into the field 'ACTIVE_AREAS' of the image pickle. this is a scitbx_array_family_flex_ext.int object. in a cctbx script, import the flex librabry, then just make it from a numpy array. Ask Nick/Aaron or the CCTBXBB if this is troublesome.

n.b. on performance We have created some pretty massive arrays here (for ease of explanation). Things will run much faster if you do these one at a time, instead of holding all the images you want to convert in memory at the same time. i.e: 1. cctbx script to convert image pickle to numpy array.* 2. use the functions shown here to create a backstop numpy array, dump it. 3. cctbx script to read this boolean array, convert it to a scitbx flex array, and put it back into the pickle. Ask Nick and Aaron for help.

*here is the one I used:

from libtbx import easy_pickle as ep
import sys

if __name__ == '__main__':
  if len(sys.argv) != 2:
    print "takes only 1 argumenr"
    sys.exit()
  pck_file = sys.argv[1]
  new_name = "numpy-" + pck_file
  img_d = ep.load(pck_file)
  img_data = img_d['DATA'].as_numpy_array()
  ep.dump(new_name, img_data)
